column168: Shipment arrived on Polar Air Cargo's airctaft from Prestwick, UK to JFK Int'l Aiport via Chicago on board flight PO605/718 02 April 2006 at 07:30. The piece was loaded on a pallet. The aircraft was off-loaded and the pallet was placed in the Alliance warehouse (Polar Air Cargo's ground handler) for breakdown and further shipping by road to Boston. When the warehouse staff started to breakdown the pallet at 20:06 they noticed an odor from the pallet and saw there was liquid on one of the drums which was labeled dangerous goods. The warehouse staff left the area and contacted the NY Port Authority Police. They came over and contacted the hazmat teaam at JFK who came over with spill equipment and removed the leaking drum.
column169: All of the spill process was followed as per protocal, the drum was inspected in PIK prior to take-off. We believe this was an isolated incident as we have had the same shipper for a long time with no previous incidents.

column168: Unloading trailer and found puddle under last skid and noticed nail had punctured 30 gallon drum.  2.5 gallons released, in house clean up.  Used 2 bags of absorbent material (clay type, particle mask and 1 roll of duct tape.  Photos were taken.
column169: Skids and nails just don't mix.  Nailed skids appear to be a great problem in this industry when transporting hazardous materials.  I realize it would be a great burden on the industry to place standards on shippers and manufacturers of hazardous materials in containers to require they be placed on plastic type skids and banded in all four directions to the skids by plastic banding, etc.  If we continue to allow this type of packaging nail punctures seem to be a part of the transportation norm.  I find no way for our loaders or drivers to have been able to see the events that have occured with this release.

column168: Drum was not properly blocked or braced and as the load went down the road the drum moved and was allowed to go into a pallet jack which caused a small hole in the drum allowing 12-16 ounces of fluid to be released.  Driver called the safety department after he had moved the drum in such a way to avoid the fluid from any further release.  At that time the driver's arms came in contact with the released material causing minor burning and irritation to the area.  After washing the chemical off his arms, the burning discontinued and the driver appears to have no after effects.
column169: All freight must be blocked and braced for transportation.  Will re-inforce this policy at this location.  Driver may receive disciplinary action.  Our policy does not allow freight to leave a terminal without proper blocking and bracing.  Our policy does not allow anyone to come in contact with released materials until such time it is determine what is being released and proper measures are determined to handle such cases.

column168: Drum was shoved forward which caused a crease in the drum, which lead to a small pin hole allowing liquid to be released.  1/2 face respirator and 1 handful of absorbent material and 1 pair of nitrile and PVC outer glove used to clean up less than 1 cup full of material.
column169: Improper blocking and bracing lead to the release of this material.  Will find out who loaded freight and re-train or discipline depending on step process level.

National Carriers (NCI) Truck was traveling in Dallas when another private vehicle stopped suddenly.  NCI truck applied the brakes hard to avoid contact; this in turn caused to load to shift.  One of the 55 gallon drums was damaged during the load shift. Driver noticed that something was leaking from the trailer and pulled over and notified the authorities and Chem Trak.
column169: Here at NCI we investigated and counseled each person involved.  A driver that picked up the load did not apply load locks.  The driver that re-powered the load also did not check for load locks all were counseled according. Proper bracing is part of our training program here and the incident could have been avoided if the drivers properly performed their duties.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While loading, 1 skid containing 3, 3.5-Liter Fiberboard boxes, 1Fiberboard box fell of the skid and was crushed between the skid and the trailer wall.  Approximately 3.5 liters of free product was released onto the trailer floor.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel performed cleanup using gloves and a plastic bag.  The free product evaporated and the damaged box was placed into 1, 55- gallon recovery drum, which will be disposed internally.  The remaining shipment will be forwarded to the consignee.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested.
column169: Since the release was accidental and the result of human error, no plans currently exist to prevent reoccurrence.

column168: FILE-06-102 DOT     SHIPPER-ALDRICH CHEMICAL     AWB#-ABE 66152801783 NES    ON 04/06/2006 AT 2015 EST, THE HAZMAT HOTLINE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM THE NORTHEAST REGIONAL HUB, LOCATED AT 70 CENTRE NEW ENGLAND WAY, COVENTRY, RI 02816.  DAVE FROM THE NORTHEAST REGIONAL HUB REPORTED THAT THEY HAD A COMPROMISED PACKAGE.  THE HOTLINE CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TEAM.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING 1X.1 KG GLASS BOTTLE OF ZINC BROMIDE.  DUE TO THE GLASS BOTTLE BEING CRUSHED, ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO THE NORTHEAST REGIONAL HUB VIA TRUCK # 6243.    THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY DECLARED AS A CORROSIVE SOLID ACIDIC INORGANIC NOS, (ZINC BROMIDE), CLASS 8, UN3260, PG II WITH THE SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED. SPILL TECHNICIANS ELWOOD BOHL AND TERY RUGGERIE DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. column168: UPON LOADING THE TRUCK THE DRUMS WERE SECURED PER SAFETY-KLEEN STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES WITH RESTRAINING STRAPS AND DRUM LIDS WERE PROPERLY CLOSED AND SECURED.  ENROUTE TO THE FINAL DESTINATION THE TRUCK WAS DIVERTED TO AN UNSCHEDULED STOP AT ANOTHER CUSTOMER LOCATION.  THEREFORE, THE DRIVER HAD TO TAKE A DIFFERENT ROUTE THAN WAS ORIGINALLY PLANNED.  THIS NEW ROUTE TOOK HIM OVER A SECTION OF SEVERELY ROUGH ROAD AND ENDED UP JOSTLING THE SECURED DRUMS SEVERELY.  THIS PUT STRESS ON THE STRAP CLOSURES BEYOND WHAT THEY WERE DESIGNED TO HANDLE AND THE STRAPS LOOSENED.  THE DRUMS THEN BECAME FREE TO BOUNCE AND THE LID OF ONE DRUM LOOSENED, THE DRUM TIPPED, AND LIQUID SPILLED INSIDE THE TRUCK.  WHILE LEAVING THE UNSCHEDULED STOP THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT APPROXIMATELY 13 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED INTO THE TRUCK'S CONTAINMENT SYSTEM AND APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE ROAD BENEATH.  THE DRIVER INITIALLY USED ABSORBANT TO CONTAIN/MITIGATE THE SPILL AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO FINISH THE CLEANUP.
column169: THE INCIDENT WILL BE REVIEWED WITH SAFETY-KLEEN PERSONNEL AND DRIVERS WILL BE ADVISED TO AVOID SUCH ROUGH TERRAIN WHEN TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column4: A specification cargo tank 1,000 gallons or greater containing any hazardous materials that (1) received structural damage to the lading retention system or damage that requires repair to a system int
column168: Our Driver pick-up loaded bins (2) at Rho-Chem's yard and proceeded to US Ecology for disposal. He was I-15 headed East bound, just passed Afton Canyon Road when he noticed smoke coming from one of the Roll-off bins. He pulled over, and called 911. He then disconnected his rear trailer and pulled forward and put the bin on the ground that was burning and disconnected from it. He then put out warning devices and helped with traffic controll.  Fire Dept arrived on site. But because the top roller doors on bin could not be opened, a hole was cut in the top of the bin and 400 gallons of foam and water distinguish the smoldering materials.  Plating bath filters that should not have been in this bin, are considered to be the reason for the fire. They are filled with small particals of metals and when dried out and exposed to air can flash.
column169: Changes in the processes used to ensure that these filters are not but into our bins in the future.  Facility Manager for Rho-Chem is seeing to the procedural changes.

column168: ON SATURDAY, APRIL 15, 10:15 AM THE HIRED MAN OF H&J BUSEMAN FARMS WAS APPLYING NH3 ON THEIR FARM.  AFTER APPLYING 36 OZ HE MADE A RIGHT TURN AND NOTICED NH3 ESCAPING NEAR THE COUPLER AREA.  IT IS BELIEVED THE COUPLER THREADS FAILED DUE TO THE WEIGHT OF THE VALVE, COUPLER, AND HOSE, OR THE HOSE COULD HAVE BEEN RAN OVER BY THE TRAILER TIRE.  I MADE THE NECESSARY CALL TO THE NRC @ 10:22 WITH DETAILS KNOWN TO ME AT THAT TIME.  THE MESERVEY FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED AS WELL AS SEVERAL MAXYIELD EMPLOYEES TO ASSIST IN CONTROL. A STRONG SE WIND AND WARM TEMPS HELPED TO KEEP THE CLOUD IN CHECK.  AT 11:15 I ARRIVED TO COMPLETE THE INVESTIGATION. (SEE ATTACHED REPORT) T.W.
column169: MINIMIZING THE WIEGHT AND LENGTH OF HOSE WILL EHLP.  ALSO MODIFYING THE BRACKET THAT HOLDS THE COUPLER IT WILL GIVE ADDITIONAL STRENGTH TO THE COUPLER ASSEMBLY.  INCREASE THE NUMBER OF INSPECTIONS BEING DONE ON TANKS.  WE BEGIN THE SEASON WITH A THOROUGH INSPECTION, AND EACH TIME THE TANK RETURNS FOR A REFILL, AN ADDITIONAL VISUAL INSPECTION IS DONE LOOKING FOR WEAR POINTS AND OTHER FLAGS THAT MAY NEED ATTENTION REQUIRING THE TANK TO BE TAKEN OUT-OF-SERVICE.  (SEE ATTACHED REPORT) T.W.

column168: FILE- 06-104 DOT AWB#- DATA POOL AWB#- RNH 47694587220 STP  ON 04/11/2006 AT 0102, A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN “C” BUILDING OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY, LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. SPILL TECHNICIAN NICHOLAS RHODES DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, HE FOUND A LAB PACK WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE INSIDE OF THE PACKAGE. HE REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, HE FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN 2 X 2 OZ PLASTIC RECEPTACLES OF DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMENS. DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE, 2 OZ OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT# 172, N9O7AX.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY DECLARED AS A DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMEN WITH THE    MARKING, “OVERWRAP FOR DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMEN SHIPMENT.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0104.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BENT BY A FORKUFT WHILE SETTING ON THE DOCKAND ABOUT 1/2 OZ OF PRODUCT SPILLED OUT. THE CONTAINER AND PRODUCT WAS RECOUPED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND PLACED IN THE HAZMAT BAY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL

column168: Driver arrived at the loading dock and discovered damaged product had leaked onto trailer floor and outside the trailer onto the pavement.  Free product impacted a storm drain one foot away from wall.  K&D Industrial Services arrived onsite to secure, contain, and remediate.  It was determined that the cleaning solution had left the catch basin traveling out the outfall pipe and entered the outfall ditch along a driveway.  Absorbant pads were used to recover free product at the outfall.  K&D pumped out the catch basin and waterblasted the pipeline to remove residual free product.  Some hand digging was performed at the outfall ditch to remove petroleum contaminated soils.  Two drums of solids and 563 gallons of petroleum contaminated water was collected for disposal at the Autumn Hills Landfill, Zeeland, MI.

column168: Product was being transferred from our cargo tank to the customer's storage tank.  When driver opened the discharge valve on the trailer to start the unload, some product ran out from the discharge assembly where the hose was hooked up.  He immediately closed the valve.  Whoever assembled the valve after trailer was washed and before loading it again, had not assembled it properly.  Driver got a few drops of product on his left arm and the rest went in a containment area.  Driver rinsed his arm as a precaution but no irritation developed and no further treatment was needed.  He had on long sleeves as opposed to the slicker suit that was required per his handling instructions for the product. Driver corrected the valve assembly problem and finished the offload.
column169: Proper procedures were not followed first by whomever assembled the valve after the trailer was washed and then by the driver that delivered the load.  He did not wear his prescribed PPE.  Proper PPE will be a big part of annual training for all our drivers.

Driver was transferring product from cargo tank to customer's storage tank.  When the level in the storage tank got to a certain height, the driver closed the valve on the trailer and went on top of trailer to see how much product was left in it.  Just as he stepped down from the trailer, the connection where the driver had hooked up to the customers line, broke off.  Some product that was in the line and hose spilled out.  Customer fixed the line and cleaned up the spill
column169: The connection that broke off was a plastic nipple.  A sturdier fittings on customer fill line may have prevented the problem.

column168: 04/03/06 at 09:05 hrs, a CSXT car inspector reported that there was a strong odor of ammonia in the air around outbound tracks, The area contained two tank cars which were both isolated. CSXT emergency response contractor, SWS, Birmingham, AL., was contacted to determine the source of the leak. Once on scene, SWS verified PLMX 35331, was the source of the leak. Inspection of the rail car found a vapor leak at the pressure relief device. Two new 0 rings were installed in the PDR and the leak stopped. A leak test was conducted on the PRD and the car was forwarded to destination.  Cause Code: 414  NARRI: 2(4+9+0)x(2+0)=52
column169: Residue cars should have reduced tank pressure. A check of all valves and fittings be performed and a periodic maintenance schedule adhered to for all tank car fittings.

While inspecting material on a a trailer that was in 10-day transit at the Onyx Envrionmental Services facility located in Blaine, MN, a small leak was discovered from a drum that contained PCB oil at less than 500 ppm. The 55 gallon drum was placed into an 85 gallon salvage drum along with the spill debris. The drum had developed a small pin hole on the bottom of the drum. This type of failure is very difficult to prevent as it is extremely difficult to detect.
column169: The incident will be reviewed with all field personnel, however small pin holes on the bottom of drums are very difficult to detect.

column168: The shipment leaked while being trucked from AZO to GRR. When the ULD was opened for transload there was an overwhelming odor eminating from the ULD. The area was evacuated and our internal hazmat team removed the 30+ packages. Two of the 30 were damaged, one was repacked and moved out, one was held for a disposition. The spilled contents and package were placed in a salvage drum. The spill occurred due to a lack of positive closure on the screw on lids and absence of cushioning and absorbent material. The FAA was notified in DTW, I spoke to SA Craig Nutt. The freight is being held pending an FAA inspection. Chemtrek was also notified.

The boxes were found leaking. Baking soda was applied to the spill to neutralize  it. The shipment was sent as a ‘Non-Spillable Battery’ shipment covered under ICAO’s USG-ll. As such the batteries aren’t supposed to spill if the battery case is cracked at 131 degrees F. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA Rich Olshef ski. The freight is being held pending an FAA inspection.

The jerrican had been set on the ground on an uneven surface, bending the seam & allow:ng the material to escape. The spill was recovered & the jerrican was placed in a salvage drum. We are holding the freight for a disposition.

column168: Steve Scheidow found this pallet leaking in a return trailer from the day prior. After looking at the pallet closely, you can see that a nail from the structure of the pallet punctured the bottom of a box. There was only one small puncture wound on the bottom of a box.
column169: Pallets need to be reinforced so nails do not become exposed and puncture the product being moved on them. However, this is a first time offense for this shipper and probably a fluke.

column168: An employee of Farmers Cooperative Society was towing two anhydrous ammonia nurse tanks behind a company pickup truck.  The wheel bolts came loose on the right hand rear wheel of the front nurse tank.  When the wheel fell off, the running gear landed on the axle hub.  This vibration caused the liquid withdrawal valve, located on top of the front nurse tank to open.  There was no mechanical defect or failure of the valve.  The valve appears to have opened due to the vibration caused from driving on the wheel hub.  The driver immediately pulled to the side of the road and exited the vehicle.  Company officails were contacted and the Plymouth County Sheriff's Office and the Akron, Iowa Volunteer Fire Department responded.  Highway C-12 was closed in both directions for approximately one hour.  The Volunteer Fire Department donned protective clothing, then approched the nurse tank and closed the valve, ending the release.  The driver of the pickup truck inhaled a small amount of ammonia vapor when he exited the vehicle.  He did not complain of any symptoms, but was checked out at the local hospital as a precautionary measure.  A small amount of vegetative burn was noted on the grass ditch along both sides of the highway.  No anhydrous ammonia reached the waters of the State.  No evacuations were required.  No clean-up or mitigation of the scene was required.
column169: Farmers Cooperative Society conducts an annual inspection of all ammonia nurse tanks.  Daily inspections of each nurse tank are also conducted, prior to transportation.  Driver's who deliver the nurse tanks have been trained to inspect the nurse tanks and running gears for any defects or deficiencies.  Company officals will review that training with each driver and ensure that each driver conducts a complete inspection, prior to transporting the nurse tank.

column168: ACFX 77670 was noted by carrier personnel with product leaking from the side of the car. Car isolated, spill contained and shipper notified. The contents of the car were transferred to ACFX 72358 for further transport and delivery. ACFX 77670 had a temporary patch applied as a precaution. The car will be sent to a certified tank car repair facility under FRA Movement Authority for further inspection and repairs.

OLNX 117085 was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of car. Car isolated and shipper notified. Shipper and consignee representatives responded and found product vapor escaping from an undetermined area inside the protective housing. All valves and fittings were tightened without stopping the release.  The car was moved under FRA Movement Authority 06040082 into the consignee’s facility for off-loading and further inspection. Inspection after unloading revealed the pressure relief device flange was not properly seated on the pressure plate allowing a slight vapor release. The PRD was properly aligned and tightened stopping the release. The car was returned to the shipper’s plant for futher inspection and repairs.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading approximately 500 gallons of free product were released due to a faulty flange.  Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. of Chicago, Illinois was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. used dry ice to harden the liquid substance and chipped the hardened product from the affected asphalt surface.  The cleanup materials and hardened product were placed into one roll-off box and eighteen 55-gallon drums for disposition.  Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated during the cleanup.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and was related to a faulty flange, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon leaving customer facility, the Kemiron Trans, Inc. driver neglected to close the dome lid on the tank, which resulted in the release.  Approximately 300 gallons of free product were released.  The free product affected the asphalt surface at the facility.  American Compliance Technologies of Bartow, Florida was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, ACT applied absorbent material to the free liquid on the asphalt surface, and proceeded to sweep the spent material from the area.  Disposal will be coordinated directly by Kemiron Trans, Inc. per local, state, and federal regulations.  Please note, originally, the release was reported to have involved approximately 1,500 gallons of free product.  However, after further inspection of the site by ACT, it was determined that approximately 300 gallons had been released.  The free product was contained to the asphalt surface.  No soil or waterways were impacted as a result of the release.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to an accident, which resulted in the failure to close the dome lid, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Kemiron Trans, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines to all personnel.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS DELIVERING FOUR TOTE BINS TO COOLBRANDS, NORTH LAWRENCE, NY.  THEY WERE LOADED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER (TWO ON THE RIGHT AND TWO ON THE LERT).  THE COLLBRANDS EMPLOYEE REMOVED THE TWO RIGHT BINS BUT COULDN'T UNLOAD THE OTHERS BECAUSE OF FREIGHT LOADED BEHIND ON THE LEFT.  WHILE USING HIS PALLET JACK TO MANEUVER THE TOTE CLEAR, THE VALVE STRUCK THE CORNER OF THE SKID BEHIND IT.  THE IMPACT CRACKED THE COLLAR BOLT RELEASING THE VALVE FROM TOTE SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASING THE PRODUCT.  THIS CONTINUED FOR APPROXIMATELY TEN MINUTES.  THE DRIVER AND EMPLOYEE EXITED THE TRIALER TO GET HELP.  THE DRIVER PULLED THE TRAILER AWAY FROM THE DOCK, PUMPED AIR INTO THE TRAILER'S AIR BAGS CAUSING THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO ELEVATE.   THIS ACTION REVERSED THE FLOW OF THE RELEASED PRODUCT CONTAINING IT IN THE TRAILER.  PRODUCT THAT LEAKED OFF THE TRAILER ENTERED A STORM DRAIN AT THEIR DOCK.  A COOLBRAND EMPLOYEE CLOSED THE DRAIN VALVE TRAPPING THE PRODUCT.  A HAZMAT CONTRACTOR LATER REMOVED THE LIQUID FROM THE STORM DRAIN.
column169: A DOOR OR HEAVY METAL SCREEN SHOULD BE INSTALLED IN FRONT OF THE VALVE IN TRANSITY.  THE CURRENT DESIGN PROTECTS EVERY THING BUT THE MOST CRITICAL AND VULNERABLE DEVICE ON THE TOTE.  THE COLLAR BOLT CRACKED AFTER THE VALVE STRUCK A PALLET WITH VERY LITTLE FORCE.  WHETHER THE CHEMICALS TRANSPORTED IN THE TOTE CONTRIBUTED OR AGE CAUSED IT TO FAIL, THE TOTE SHOULD BE CHECKED PERIODICALLY.  THERE ARE NO MARKINGS ON THE TOTE TO INDICATE A PERIODIC INSPECTION PROGRAM.

column168: BNSF mechanical inspector reported UTLX 203071 in railyard leaking product from the top fittings which dripped down the side shell. BNSF response contractor reported finding the 3 inch liquid line valve as the leak source. The valve’s stem packing nut or packing retainer was approximately 2 turns loose. Responders tool tightened this packing nut by 1400 hrs. MDT, 4/10/06 ending any further product release. Responders monitored UTLX 203071 for another hour to ensure no additional product leaks observed. Response concluded by 1500 hrs. MDT, 4/10/06. All spillage evaporated either on the shell or atop the tank cars drip ledge.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: During switching in railyard, the CMC RR switch crew reported ECUX 355120 with fresh product spillage on its’ side shell. ECUX 355120 was carefully moved to an isolated area in the railyard to await repairs. BNSF contract responders removed seal 0107720 from the protective housing cover to inspect the valves. Responders found the vapor valve finger loose atop its’ threaded connection on a threaded pipe nipple. Responders removed valve, cleaned and Teflon taped the threaded connections. The valve was replaced on the pipe nipple and tool tightened. The manway was opened to check product outage and the outage levels were deemed appropriate. The manway closure was resecured. No further product leakage observed and the contract responders demobilized at 1350 hrs. CDT, 4/12/06. All spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Roll-by inspection by BNSF personnel of a BNSF westbound train traveling on the main track resulted in the train crew being notified that an entrained covered hopper (GCCX 70279) was leaking product from one of its’ three bottom outlets. The train crew setout GCCX 70279 on a side track at Thedford, NE for mechanical inspection and repair by 1820 hrs. CDT 4/12/06. The local volunteer fire department was called to ensure no spillage impacted any sensitive environmental receptors. BNSF mechanical responders found the B-end bottom outlet closure slightly ajar and these responders closed and sealed this outlet by 2205 hrs. CDT, 4/12/06. A hazardous material contractor with a vac truck was called to vacuum the product spillage from under the rail car and any other product found nearby. This was accomplished by noon on 4/13/06. A BNSF hazardous material responder also inspected CCCX 70279 after it was repaired and no further product leakage was evident. This responder did replace all four placards on GCCX 70279, as two were found crinkled and the other two were partially torn.

column168: Our truck was traveling eastbound on Rte 287 in West Chester County New York at approximately 4:30 in the morning. When approaching the 7.7 mile marker our driver  came upon a unoccupied vehicle that had been involved in a one vehicle accident and was disabled in the middle of the road with no lights or any other type of warning visible. Our driver swerved to the right to avoid the disabled vehicle and when doing so clipped the right front corner of the vehicle which in turn disabled his left front steer tire. As a result the truck was driven to the left into a cement "Jersey" barrier and slid against it until it came to a rest. While sliding against the cement road divider the friction cause the wheel/tire assembly to ignite which in turn ignited the trailer floor. The inner contents of the trailer contained a flammable shipment which further wicked the remaining non-hazardous shipments on board. The local fire department responded to the scene and proceeded to extinguish the fire through conventional fire fighting medians. The runoff from the fire mitigation entered and traveled through the storm water runoff system and eventually deposited and contaminated a 300 foot section of dry creek bed. The trailer was a total loss as was the contents it was carrying. The destroyed trailer was removed from the scene along with the charred contents and disposed of accordingly in accordance with all local, State and Federal regulations.. All contaminated lanes of Rte 287 were pressure washed and scrubbed to remove all traces of spilled products. The storm water runoff system was hydro-jetted and the runoff captured and properly disposed of. The contaminated soil in the dry creek bed was removed and properly disposed of. The remove soil was replaced with stone rip-rap and restored according through direction of State and local authorities.

THE DRIVER, DANNIE MCNELL, HAS BEEN WORKING WITH INDUSTRIAL & AG CHEMICALS, INC.(IAC, INC) SINC 1986. THUS, I WOULD CONSIDER DANNIE VERY EXPERIENCED. DANNIE DROVE OFF THE ROAD OFF THE ROAD AND HIT  A MUD PUDDLE WHILE TRYING TO EASE BACK ONTO THE ROAD THE TRUCK STARTED LEANING TOO FAR OVER AND THE TRUCK OVERTURNED ON ITS RIGHT SIDE.  AS A RESULT OF THE FLATBED TRAILER TURNING COMPLETELY UPSIDE DOWN, THE PACKAGES WERE RUPTURED CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 500 POUNDS OF MATERIAL TO SPILL OUT. THE STATE TRANSPORT POLICE WAS ON THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY.  THE COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE. AS WELL AS OTHER LOCAL AUTHROITIES.  DANNIE THEN NOTIFIED HIS DISPATCHER AS WELL AS MYSELF.  THE SPILL WAS BASICALLY MONITORED TO MAKE SURE NO CARS DROVE WITHIN SO MANY FEET OF THE SPILL.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ONSITE FOR PRECAUTIONS SINCE THE VEHICLE WAS OVERTURNED.  IAC INC DID CALL A LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY TO GO AND LOAD THE BINS AS WELL AS ANY SPILLAGE INTO ROLL ON ROLL OFF CONTAINERS AND MOVE THEM FROM THE SCENE.
column169: WE ARE CURRENTLY REVIEWING OUR REGULATIONS AND CONDUCTING ONSITE TRAINING TO OUR DRIVERS.  OUR DISPATCHER HAS RECEIVED SOME ADDITIONAL TRAINING FROM ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCE CENTER IN CARY, NC TO BETTER SERVICE OUR DRIVERS.  JJ KELLER AND ASSOCIATES HAVE PUT TOGETHER TRAINING PROGRAMS FOR OUR DRIVERS AS WELL.  IAC, INC IS ALSO TALKING WITH MATERIAL CONTAINMENT INC TO LOOK INTO THE DIFFERENT TYPES OF BINS AVAILABLE.

column168: On April 8, 2006, at approximately 5:30am, a rollover accident occurred involving a Motiva Enterprises delivery vehicle. The vehicle was carrying 9002 gallons of gasoline for delivery to a service station in Osprey, Florida. After the accident, the tractor came to rest upright while the tractor was on its right side. The fuel tank of the tractor ruptured, spilling approximately 60 gallons of own consumption Low Sulfur Diesel fuel. The tanker trailer did not rupture; however, one dome cover had a small leak which resulted in a spill of about 30 gallons of regular unleaded gasoline. Police, local fire departments, Haz-Mat teams and Motiva’s contract OSRO responded to the incident. The spill area was limited mainly to the roadway, with a small amount reaching a 2 ft. strip in the median. Approximately 20 cubic yards of soil will be removed during the remediation process. Mitigation efforts included securing of the dome covers on the trailer, use of sorbent materials, berming off any drainage areas and pumping out the overturned unit. There was no accumulation of product in any area that was recoverable.
column169: Actions taken to prevent recurrence:  • Incident was thoroughly discussed with all Motiva Enterprises drivers at a monthly safety meeting  • Company safety representative will reinforce Smith Defensive Driving techniques during annual training in May.  • Annual driver check rides will be conducted in June and Smith System defensive driving will be emphasized.

Sequence of events:  • An operator began loading a tank car at approximately 10:30 pm.on April 8, 2006  • At 1:45 a.m. the operator observed material spilling from the tank car.  • The valve at the tank car was immediately closed and the pump was turned off.  • The material spilled onto the track pan below the tank car and overflowed into the adjacent gravel area. The material made it to the storm sewer ballast drains beneath the tracks. (Note:  storm water from the facility is normally pumped to the in-house process sewer treatment system which discharges to the municipal POTW). An isolation valve immediately downstream of the spill was closed to isolate the material within the storm sewer. The waters from the isolated pit were pumped into the process sewer. No material left the site.  • Material in the track pan and in the accompanying sump was pumped to a RCRA storage tank.  • A low spot was dug in the gravel and the collected material was pumped into the sump.  Package failure:  A float that indicates the level in the tank car was found damaged due to deterioration and aging therefore there was no visual indication of the level in the tank car.  Duration of release:  The release was less than 10 minutes.
column169: • The float indicator was replaced.  • The operator was given follow-up training emphasizing the need to pay closer attention during loading operations.    Note:  • The initial determination was that the spill of this sodium hydrosulfide mixture was less than the RQ (2272 gallons) for this material, based on the time the operator was away and the visual observation of the in-house emergency responders. The actual amount would be determined when the T/C was weighed and compared to the storage tank level reading.  • On April 11, 2006 the tank car was weighed and the ensuing calculations from the storage tank level showed that apparently 2600 gallons (26,000 pounds) had been released, which was in excess of the RQ. Although the visual observation dicE not support this amount, it was reported as an RQ release.  • Upon further review following the release reporting it became evident that the storage tank liquid level indication was in error and that the amount of the spill had been over reported. Also, it was determined by lab analysis, that the percentage of sodium hydrosulfide in the mixture was only 7%, compared to the conservative MSDS value of 22%.  • Based on pumping rate and the time the operator was away from the loading operation it was determined that the entire spill was 607 gallons (6075 pounds) and that the sodium hydrosulfide amount was 425 pounds, which is below the 5,000 pound RQ for sodium hydrosulphide.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Deterioration or Aging
column168: Upon arrival at our Auburn facility on Friday April 14, a small crack was identified in one of three plastic IBCs at the top of the inner container. The damaged container was held at our facility and the shipper was notified.  The shipper came to our facility to transfer the material into another IBC on Monday afternoon April 17, but did not bring a pump or means of transferring the material, so they left the replacement IBC along with the damaged IBC in a trailer with the intent of coming back the next day.  At approximately 1730, a yard hostler moved the trailer that contained both IBCs only from our loading dock to our holding yard.  Another employee noticed liquid leaking from the back of the trailer and alerted the hostler.  Employees effectively dammed the area around the trailer to prevent the spread of the material as possible.  The area around the trailer was isolated.  City of Auburn Fire Dept responded.  Notifications were made to the National Spill Response Center and the Washington Department of Ecology.  A Hazmat response team from NRC Environmental responded and identified two spider web cracks in the inside plastic container that allowed the material to leak.  The two cracks were approximately 8 to 12 inches in diameter along the top edges and side of the plastic tote.  NRC Environmental indicated that the plastic container had become brittle and weakened due to exposure to heat and/or cold.  The material leaked onto the ground for twenty to thirty minutes prior to containment and was approached cautiously.  The cleanup continued over two days.  Contamination was limited to asphalt where the material was neutralized and a strip of lawn adjoining the lot approximately 20' by 40'.
column169: From our understanding the incident was the result of cracks in a plastic IBC that was in a brittle or weakened condition.  (NRC Environmental reported that they were able to poke a hole in the plastic with a finger)  With inside pressure of the liquid, our driver could not have identifed the weakness or nature of the material at the pickup point.  The spill and resulting damage could have been avoided by proper storage of empty containers.

column168: Driver was making 3 separate deliveries from the cargo tank.  It was a flammable load so he was using nitrogen to clear his line after the deliveries.  He only had nitrogen for 2 deliveries.  When he was disconnecting the hose from the other delivery, there was more product in the hose than he had anticipated and it spilled out.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: Sequence of events:  • An operator began unloading a tank car at approximately 11:00 p.m.  • At 1:00 a.m. the operator observed material overflowing from the storage tank.  • The unloading pump was turned off.  • The material spilled into a clay-based/gravel secondary containment area, flowing to a nearby low area that drains to the process sewer. The process sewer valve is normally closed, unless draining the area, and the valve was confirmed secured. No material made it to the storm sewer or left the site.  • Pumps on adjacent tanks were shutoff as a precaution to prevent ignition of vapors.  • In-house emergency response personnel sprayed foam over the entire area to minimize vapor release.  • Approximately 1250 gallons was pumped out of the tank to another tank to lower the level in the overfilled storage tank.  • Material in the low area of the tank farm was pumped to a portable tank and then transferred to a permitted RCRA storage tank.  • The area was continually flushed with water. The water/petroleum naphtha mixture was transferred to a tank truck and then transferred to a permitted RCRA storage tank. Over 12,000 gallons of water flushing and material was collected.  • Additional water flushing was determined to be acceptable to put directly to the in-house process sewer treatment system which discharges to the municipal POTW.
column169: • This tank had been put into this service the previous month. A typographical error occurred when transmitting the safe tops level reading to the operating personnel.  • A spreadsheet is used to calculate the safe tops for a storage tank. The calculation uses the outage on the tank along with the specific gravity and temperature to determine the safe tops. The size of the tank in gallons is also included in the spreadsheet, but was not needed in any of the calculations. A separate line has been added that uses the size of the tank to give a second check for the safe tops calculation. The cross check calculation will ensure that a typo has not occurred and prevent a recurrence of the release.

column25: EXEL TRANSPORTATION SERVICES FOR HUB GROUP INC
column168: Intermodal trailer ICEZ 530018 reported leaking an unknown green liquid substance during deramping from the inbound intermodal flatcar at the BNSF intermodal facility. ICEZ 530018 was taken to the containment area for further investigation. Contract responders found one metal caged IBC with the inner plastic receptacle compromised. The rigid plastic inner receptacle had a small stress fracture/crack in the lower to mid left corner of this receptacle. The root cause of this fracture could not be determined, but the lading inside trailer was insufficiently blocked and braced. All lading was removed and transferred into another intermodal container for furtherance. The remaining commodity inside the IBC was transferred into a recovery drum and placed with the other transferred lading. The spillage inside of ICEZ 530018 was neutralized and cleaned, but the spilled commodity damaged parts of the interior metal flooring. Spillage atop the paved surfaces at the intermodal facility was also neutralized and water washed.

column168: BNSF switch crew reported GATX 11951 in railyard with fresh liquid on its’ side shell. GATX 11951 was cordoned off in the railyard. BNSF contract and shipper emergency response teams responded. Responders determined that the frangible disc had ruptured from internal pressure and expelled a small quantity of product from the hole in the frangible disc during the rupture event. The frangible disc was replaced in kind and secured. Responders neutralized the spillage on the tank shell and wiped the neutralized residue. No product impacted the ground. Response concluded by 0700 hrs. CDT, 4/13/06.

On 04/17/06 at 0029 hrs., the PCC notified Hazardous Material Group advising tank car TILX 320025 was leaking from the top of the car while it was switched from the train yard to the repair track for repairs to the air brake system. The car was isolated at the repair track. Chemtrec was notifled#04172006001. The shipper, Ineos Phenol, notified CSXT that they would dispatch their response team to inspect the leak The response team discovered that the liquid line valve was slightly open and the plug was less then tool tight. The liquid line valve was closed and the plug was tightened. The stem packing gland for the liquid operating stem was tightened and the leak stopped. The shipper was advised the rail car was improperly stenciled, AAR211. They contacted the tank car builder who provided information to FRA showing the railcar was built to DOT111 standards. FRA movement approval was issued for continuance.    Cause Code: 662  NARRI: 5(5+3+0)x(2+0)=80

column168: IMTT personnel were loading Langer Trailer #2285 and at approximately half-way through the loading chattering was heard coming from the rear external valve which was being utilized.  The operator shut down and checked the valve it appeared OK.  Upon resuming the stem of the valve shot out of the valve followed by a guizer of product.  The operator shut down the transfer and closed the loading valve and internal valve on the trailer however the internal valve was slightly leaking.  During the incident the IMTT employee was lightly sprayed on the legs and exposed to fumes.  The employee immedately removed contaminated clothing and footware.  The employee showered and declined medical evaluation.    The Langer Director of Safety and Personnel responded to the site and particpated with the onsite ERT in securring the trailer and replacing the affected valve so the trailer could leave the site for further evaluation.  The product was shipped on another Langer trailer.
column169: Upon examination of the valve on the day of the incident it appears the cotter pin holding the valve assemble together was missing and could not be located during the repair.  At the time of this report it remains unclear if the valve was re-assembled and installed without the cotter-pin after cleaning of the trailer or the cotter-pin broke and dislodged and was lost in this product or other products.  It appears that after use the valve became loose over time.  IMTT has had no further communication with the carrier regarding any other findings or conclusions.

THE UNLOADER HAD GOTTEN A SAMPLE FROM THE TRAILER WITHOUT THE DRIVERS KNOWLEDGE. HE HAD LEFT A BUCKET ON THE GROUND UNDER THE UNLOADING VALVE OF THE TRAILER WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IN IT. THE DRIVER NEEDED TO MOVE FORWARD A LITTLE TO BE IN A BETTER POSITION TO UNLOAD AND WHEN HE PULLED THE TRACTOR/TRAILER FORWARD HE KNOCKED OVER THE BUCKET. THE PRODUCT THAT SPILLED WAS IN A 5 GALLON PLASTIC BUCKET. THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS MISCOMMUNICATION LEADING TO HUMAN ERROR.
column169: DRIVER WAS BROUGHT IN TO HIS OPERATING CENTER FOR A SPILL REMEDIAL DISCUSSION. THE DRIVER IS TAUGHT TO ALWAYS DO A PRETRIP PRIOR TO MOVING HIS EQUIPMENT. THE DRIVER DID NOT DO THIS IN THIS PARTICULAR INCIDENT AND IF HE HAD, HE WOULD HAVE SEEN THE BUCKET AND THE SPILL WOULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED.

column168: The driver had finsihed unloading the product and was having a problem blowing the line clear of the product. The Consignee hooked up their nitgrogen to help blow the line clean. The pressure from the nitrogen seperated the male fitting on the discharge hose causing it to come off of the unload valve of the trailer allowing the spillage to occur. The Consignee and the Driver cleaned up the spill which was in a containment area by scooping it up after it dried and properly disposed of it.
column169: It is believed that the male fitting on the end of the dischage hose must not have been secure enough. The driver has been retrained and instructed on how to inspect dischage hoses to help identify a possible issue such as this in the future prior to the delivery.  The hose was returned to our hose supplier where it was repaired and tested prior to being put back in service.

column168: During an inspection in the railyard, a FRA inspector reported finding DBUX 300417 with fresh product wetness on its tank shell. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder reported finding one of the six manway securement bolts not tool tight. Inspection of the manway gasket revealed that the gasket appeared worn or aged and was not likely sealing properly. Responder applied silicone sealant around the gasket area and properly tool tightened the manway securement bolts. Spillage did not impact the ground and it was wiped from the tank car shell with absorbent pads. Response concluded at 1305 hrs. PDT, 4/17/06. DBUX 300417 was released to be delivered to the local area consignee.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Driver had connected to customer’s tank to deliver anhydrous ammonia.  When he started his pump to begin transferring material, he heard a hissing sound coming from the transfer hose.  He immediately turned the pump off and checked the bleeder valves.  The one on the angle valve was found to be partially open.  He closed the valve and notified the customer.  Customer applied their deluge spray system.  Driver resumed the delivery without further incident.  Approximately ½ pound of ammonia was estimated to have been released.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.    NOTE THAT ONLINE SYSTEM DOES NOT ALLOW FOR RELEASE AMOUNTS <1, SO 1 POUND WAS ENTERED AS THE RELEASE AMOUNT EVEN THOUGH THE ESTIMATE WAS APPROX. A HALF A POUND.

column168: Superior Carriers driver was traveling north on Hwy 65 near Tallulah, LA when he suddenly encountered a severe thunderstorm that produced heavy rains, winds and hail.  The thunderstorm caused the top of a tree to break off and fall onto the cab of the driver's tractor.  This event caused the driver to lose control and leave the traveled portion of the roadway and into a field.  The unit proceeded to collide with another tree and finnally come to rest when the unit collided with a second tree.  The collision with the second tree caused a puncture of the front bulk head of the trailer the approximate size of a quarter or 1 inch.    The LA State Police Hazardous Material Response Team responded and took charge of the accident scene.  Superior Carriers dispatched a hazardous material clean-up crew to the scene to assist with the clean up and disposal of the contaminated soil and other materials.    The LA State Police Hazardous Material Response Team decided that the best course of action to be taken was to let the product solidfy.  The exterior wrapping and insulation was removed and sprayed with water to expedite the process.  After the product had solidified (appx 2 days)the leak stopped.  The trailer was lifted by crane onto a drop deck trailer and transported to the Superior Carriers terminal in Sulphur LA.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Vacuum Relief Valve
column168: After a BNSF train crew change at Keddie, CA, the outbound crew began train movement on the main track and after about 30 car lengths of train movement; the southbound train went into an emergency air brake application. The train crew inspecting their train found five railcars derailed including one tank car (PROX 40438) derailed on its side. The cause of this derailment was contributed to the cross level of the track (not at rail joints) north of the derailment site being irregular. A small amount of product released from PROX 40438 via the vacuum relief valve (VRV) and the bottom outlet valve (BOV). The external BOV was sheared off but the internal ball valve was intact, but a small drip ensued. Within an hour after their arrival, local F.D. responders were able to wrap the VRV with plastic and secured it with tape which slowed the drips. Buckets were placed under the VRV. PROX 40438 was uprighted and set atop blocks, clear of the main track by 0130 hrs. PDT, 4/20/06. Buckets were placed under PROX 40438 to catch any drippage from the BOV. The product in PROX 40438 was offloaded into vacuum trucks with completion by 1800 hrs. PDT, 4/20/06. The off loaded product was earmarked for energy recovery disposal.

column168: BNSF roll-by inspection of a westbound train at BNSF station DoubleA revealed entrained GATX 25789 steadily dripping liquid from the bottom of this tank car. Train crew setout GATX 25789 at the north setout track (#4295) at Seligman, AZ. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder placed lined tubs under GATX 25789 to catch any escaping liquid. By 2000 hrs. MDT (4/19/06), the leak had slowed to a drip with approximately two gallons accumulating in the receptacle. BNSF and contract responders determined that most likely a compromise in the tank shell possibly caused by rubber liner failure. It appeared that welding of several broken support brackets attaching the upper guard railing had occurred. The welding atop the shell may have heated and compromised the rubber lining. Product leaked through the compromised liner, gravitated to the sump area and released. The product in GATX 25789 was transferred into UTLX 130271 on 4/21/06 without incident. Afterwards, when moving GATX 25789, product heel escaped from the sump area. Contract responders sealed the area around the sump to ensure no residue product that remained inside GATX 25789 would readily leak out during transit to a repair facility. FRA-06050116 was granted to move GATX 25789 to the repair facility. Contract responders neutralized spillage that impacted the ground and appropriately disposed of all recovered neutralized solution.

column168: ECOFLO arrived at Indian Head Naval Weapons Center (Indian Head, MD) for the removal of 20 containers of nitroform waste. Nitroform consists of 70-75% water, 30-35% of trinitromethane, and <1% urea as a stabilizer. Each container was a 30-gallon metal drum with a plastic liner and each appeared to be in good condition (non-leaking). Containers were overpacked into 55-gallon metal open head drums for transport to ECOFLO's facility in York, PA. In route six of the original twenty drums began to react creating an acid cloud (nitric acid is a precursor to trinitromethane). Three drums reacted completely. Three drums reacted partially. Fourteen drums did not react. The six drums that reacted had inner containers inverted into the overpacked outer container.    Reaction occured for several hours (four to five) with local, State and private HAZMAT firms on hand. Residuals were neutralized (with soda ash) and/or flushed with water by the local and State HAZMAT teams. Following the completion of the reaction, ECOFLO's private contractor (HMHTTC) consolidated solid residuals and debris generated during the reaction and overpacked all 20 containers into 95-gallon poly salvage drums. All drums and waste were reloaded onto ECOFLO's vehicle for completion of trip to ECOFLO's York, PA yard for further testing and evaluation.    The inner plastic containers on the 30-gallon drums are suspected to have failed that caused the contents to release and react with the two outer containers (the 30 gallon and the 55 gallon metal drums).     14 of the drums that were not involved in the reaction were returned to Navy facility at Indian Head, MD on Friday June 16, 2006    The three drums that reacted totally along with the debris from the initial cleanup was shipped to ECOFLO in Greensboro, NC for disposal    The three drums that partially reacted were consolidated into one 30-gallon poly drum on Friday, June 16, 2006 and await final disposition by the Navy.
column169: Investigation into the actual composition of this material (primary component is trinitromethane) is ongoing. It is critical to receive current data on age of this material and up-to-date analysis reflecting the amount of stabilizer added (and date added) to confirm or determine stability.    During the overpacking process, containers should be overpacked in an upright manner.    Overpacks/outer containers should always be suitable for the contents of inner containers regardless of the condition of the inner container.

column168: Upon arrival to the consignee, a small leak of red epoxy primer was noted coming out of the rear trailer doors.  Three damaged 5-gallon buckets were found to have leaked through the lids at the trailer door.  The three containers were moved and secured on the truck, then the remainder of the load was received by the consignee.  The driver then drove to the nearest Werner Enterprises drop yard to meet a clean up crew.  Upon arrival to the site, the cleanup crew applied granular sorbents to absorb any free product.  This material was swept up and placed into one 55-gallon drum.  The three damaged buckets were also overpacked into this 55-gallon drum.  The drum was then sent for proper disposal to an FDEP Permitted Hazardous Waste facility.  The entire cleanup took approximately 1.5 hours.
column169: A reccomendation could be made for the use of closed top 5-gallon buckets.  This would probably contain the material better should a bucket fall over during transportation.

column168: OUR TRACTOR/TANKER WAS MAKING A RIGHT HAND TURN INTO A GAS STATION THAT WE WERE DELIVERING PRODUCT TO. UPON TURNING, THE VEHICLE BEHIND OUR UNIT DID NOT SLOW DOWN/STOP AND PROCEEDED TO IMPACT OR PETROLEUM TANKER. AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISON, FOUR OF THE FIVE UNLOADING HEADS WERE RIPPED OFF. THE PRODUCT LOCATED IN THE LOADING TUBES (APPROXIMATELY 60-80 GALS) SPILLED ONTO THE CAR. THE CARE IMMEDIATELY CAUGHT ON FIRE, WHICH RESULTED IN THE TANKER CATCHING ON FIRE. BOTH OCCUPANTS IN EACH VEHICLE WERE ABLE TO GET OUT WITH NO INJURIES. AS THE TANKER CONTINUED TO BURN, SOME PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. UPON ARRIVAL OF THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT, THEY BEGAN APPLYING WATER TO THE FIRE, WHICH RESULTED IN WATER & PETROLEUM RUN-OFF. NO OTHER PARTS ON THE TANKER WERE COMPROMISED.
column169: THE ONLY SOLUTION TO PREVENTING THIS TYPE OF OCCURENCE WOULD BE THE ABILITY TO CLEAR PRODUCT OUT OF THE LOADING/UNLOADING LINES ON THE PETROLEUM TANKER. IF THE 60-80 GALLONS OF PETROLEUM HADN'T BEEN PRESENT, THEN THE INITIAL VEHICLE FIRE WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN CREATED. THE INCIDENT WOULD HAVE MUCH LESS SEVERE.

WHEN IT TURNED OVER SAFETY CAGE BROKE, FIRST THEN THE 3 VALVES UNDER IT WERE BROKEN OFF. ENTIRE RELEASE WENT INTO AN OPEN FIELD. NO PEOPLE WERE INJURED AT ANY TIME DURING RELEASE. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 11:30 AM ON THURSDAY APRIL 27, 2006 EMPLOYEE (CHERRY HILL FUEL TRUCK DRIVER) DISCOVERED THAT HER FUEL TRUCK NUMBER 338, WHICH WAS PARKED ON THE EASTBOUND SIDE OF VAN NESS STREET N.W. WASHINGTON, D.C. HAD BEGUN TO LEAK DIESEL FUEL. EMPLOYEE INDICATED THAT SHE HAD COMPLETED FUELING EQUIPMENT ON THE SITE AND LEFT HER TRUCK PARKED ON THE EASTBOUND SIDE OF VAN NESS STREET WHILE SHE WENT UP TO THE CHERRY HILL OFFICE TRAILER. SHE WAS WALKING BACK TO HER TRUCK FROM THE TRAILER AND WAS AT THE INTERSECTION OF INTERNATIONAL DRIVE AND VAN NESS WHEN SHE NOTICED THE LEAK. UPON INVESTIGATION, EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED THAT THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY FAILURE OF A HOSE COUPLING ON THE LINE FROM THE MAIN TANK TO THE PUMP. THE LEAK ORIGINATED AROUND THE COUPLING AND THERE WAS NOT A “HOLE” IN THE LINE IT WOULD BE BETTER DESCRIBED AS A SEPARATION OF THE METAL COUPLING FROM THE LINE. THE ESTIMATED DURATION OF THE RELEASE IS 8-10 MINUTES. THE ABSORBENT THAT WAS STORED ON THE FUEL TRUCK WAS DEPLOYED IMMEDIATELY.     OTHER CHERRY HILL PERSONNEL RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED FUEL. ANOTHER MALE EMPLOYEE (CHERRY HILL SUPERINTENDENT) HAD THE ON-SITE SPILL KIT BROUGHT TO THE SCENE AND DEPLOYED MORE ABSORBENT AS WELL AS ABSORBENT PADS. AT APPROXIMATELY 11:40 AM MALE EMPLOYEE CALLED ME TO NOTIFY ME OF THE SPILL. I ASKED HIM IF HE WANTED ME TO BRING THE SPILL KIT FROM OUR TAYLOR STREET BRIDGE PROJECT AND HE RESPONDED IN THE AFFIRMATIVE. I LOADED THE SPILL KIT AND PROCEEDED TOWARD THE CHINA EMBASSY PROJECT. I CALLED MY SUPERVISOR (CHERRY HILL SAFETY DIRECTOR) TO NOTIFY HIM OF THE SPILL AND HE INFORMED ME THAT HE WAS ALREADY AWARE OF THE SPILL AND THAT CLEAN VENTURES (CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR) HAD ALREADY BEEN NOTIFIED AND WAS PREPARING TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL.    AT APPROXIMATELY 12:10-12:15 PM I ARRIVED ON THE SCENE. I NOTED THE FUEL TRUCK WAS PARKED JUST EAST OF THE SITE ACCESS CLOSEST TO THE SINGAPORE EMBASSY AND A STREAM OF FUEL HAD TRAVELED FROM THE TRUCK DOWNHILL TOWARD CONNECTICUT AVENUE. I ALSO NOTED CHERRY HILL PERSONNEL SPREADING ABSORBENT IN THE INTERSECTION OF INTERNATIONAL DRIVE AND VAN NESS.     THE ABSORBENT AND PADS FROM THE SPILL KIT I BROUGHT WERE IMMEDIATELY PLACED ON THE FUEL IN THE INTERSECTION OF INTERNATIONAL DRIVE AND VAN NESS. AS THE ABSORBENT WAS BEING PLACED I HEARD SIRENS FROM DCFD EQUIPMENT.     ONCE DCFD ARRIVED I SOUGHT OUT THE INCIDENT COMMANDER (BATTALION CHIEF - NO NAME) TO NOTIFY HIM THAT DCFD SHOULD CHECK THE OUTFALL OF THE STORM SEWER FOR POSSIBLE FUEL. HE SENT DCFD PERSONNEL TO SOAPSTONE TO CHECK ON THE STATUS AND BASED UPON THE FACT THAT CHERRY HILL WAS ACTIVELY CLEANING THE SPILL AND HAD A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR ON THE WAY HE REMOVED THE DCFD EQUIPMENT AND PERSONNEL FROM THE SCENE. THE CAPT. (SOD BATTALION CHIEF) REMAINED ON THE SCENE. HE ADVISED THAT HE IS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE BATTALION THAT INCLUDES HAZMAT. ADDITION CHERRY HILL PERSONNEL AND ABSORBENT MATERIALS ARRIVED ON-SITE.     ANOTHER CHERRY HILL FUEL TRUCK NUMBER 343 AR

column168: 2010080629   Harris Transportation Company, LLC   Incident #5606   April 28, 2006 Incident Summary   When: Friday, April 28, 2006 at approx. 0130.   Where: Chevron Station at 8710 SW Hall Blvd. Beaverton, OR   Who: The driver involved was Richard Trembly, located out of our Portland Terminal. Mr. Trembly started with Harris on October 6, 1993.   What: Harris Transportation Company, LLC truck and trailer 280/281 arrived to unload fuel at the Chevron Station on Hall Blvd. IvIr. Trembly connected his delivery hose to the fitting on the midgrade tank. When he opened the valve to start flow, the camlock ears were not secure to the fitting and the hose came off the fitting spilling gasoline onto the concrete and asphalt area. The product traveled down the parking area towards a drain. Mr. Trembly started laying out absorbent pads to minimize the spill. Mike Dailey and Ken Lutz arrived to clean up the spill area. Absorbent material was spread out over the entire spill area and swept up into bags and taken back to the terminal for disposal.. The drain grate was removed and pads placed in the drain to absorb any fuel that may have entered the drain. The level in the drain was below the run off discharge line.   Contributing Factors: [Mr. Trembly did not secure the camlock ears on the delivery hose to the fitting before opening up the product flow.   Loss Information: Approx. 20—25 gals of gas spilled onto the area around the tank. The station was closed at the time and had no impact to the public. The spill was   reported to the following agencies:   Oregon Emergency Response (Kathy) — Case #061108 0715   Oregon DEQ (Julie Berdt) 0725   National Response Center (Miss Johnson) — Report # 795452 0730   EPA (Calvin Terads) 0800   Insurance Information: Not reported to Insurance

column168: At approximately 0615 hours, 4-12-06 a slow leak on the liquid oxygen storage tank was discovered by building maintenance personnel at the Apria Healthcare facility at 7803 E. Osie, Wichita, KS. The branch management and the Wichita Fire Department were immediately contacted.    The fire department arrived at 0631:39 and made entrance to the locked fence surrounding the tank. They found a valve that was slightly open, closed the valve and stopped the leak. The leak was onto the concrete pad and due to the slow volume of the release it simply vaporated. At 0710:20 they declared the leak secured, area safe and departed the scene. They estimated that approximately 10 gallons of oxygen, refrigerated liquid had been released.    Investigation determined that on the afternoon of 4-11-06 John Haartje, Logistics Supervisor had locked the tank valve and access gate. Apria employees Mark Descher, Transportation Lead and Larry Ervin, Patient Service Technician, witnessed this. At that time the valve appeared to be functioning properly.    On 4-17-06 a technician from BOC Gases, which is contracted for maintenance and LOX supply, inspected the tank and found everything functioning properly. He advised that there had been instances of theft by unknown subjects of cryogenic liquids in the area for use in clandestine drug operations.    There was no injuries or collateral damage as a result of this leak.
column169: Refresher training related to the tank operation and security was conducted

column168: Our driver, Gerald Hill, was operating bobtail # D586 southbound on County Road 68 when a passenger vehicle headed northbound crossed the center line causing a head on collision.  The impact caused the axel to be knocked out from under the bobtail which in turn casued the front of the truck to hit the pavement, spin and come to rest on it's passenger side.  Approximately 3-5 gallons of liquid propane was released from the relief valve.  The relief valve was not damaged nor did it ever touch the gound.  The tank sustained a large dent and scrape on the passenger side and most likely the release at the relief valve was caused by the build up of pressure sustained from the trauma of the accident.  Approximately 2-3 gallons of liquid propane was released at a small fitting on the truck meter.  The fitting was knocked off in the crash.  We do not have the police report yet from the Washington State Police, but it has been ordered.  The Washington State Police could not provide us with a report number.
column169: According to our driver and other witnesses the driver of the passenger vehicle veered over into the oncoming lane at the last second giving our driver no time to react.  Two other witnesses were interviewed by the Washington State Patrol.  One witness was directly behind the passenger vehicle involved in the crash and the other witness was working in a nearby field.

column168: CSXT Trainmaster, D. Harris, reported that at 20:00 hours on 04/03/2006, CSXT conductor M. J. Carter was walking a track and smelled a rotten egg odor coming from SHPX 206513, loaded tank car of Sulfur, Molten. Ms. Carter indicated the odor triggered an asthma attack. She was transported to the hospital. She was treated for asthma and released without restriction. Sunpro was dispatched by CSXT and found 2 of 8 manway cover bolts on SHPX 206513 were less that tool tight.  Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5(5+1+0)x(2+2)= 120
column169: CSXT MANAGER-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FIELD SERVICES, T.J. MANNAS, CONTACTED MR. D SAMPSON, SUPERVISOR OF LOADING OPERATIONS, CITGO PETROLEUM, LEMONT, IL, ON 04/06/06 AND DISCUSSED THE MATTER WITH HIM FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: CSX Haz-Mat received a call from Greg Carlo, General Car Foreman, Cumberland, MD., advising that NATX 37869 was leaking from the bottom outlet valve. An unsuccessful attempt was made to seat the valve and tighten the cap. This did not stop the leak. CSX Haz-Mat made shipper notification, Chemtrec report #04132006086. The shipper contacted car owner, GE, who responded Rescar, Elk Mills, Md., to repair the car. CSX Haz-Mat was notified that Rescar could not make the necessary repairs to the bottom outlet while under load. CSX Haz-Mat dispatched Specialized Professional Services, (Drew McCarty 877-228-7774) to respond to perform a transfer. SPSI performed a tank car to tank truck transfer of the material. The lading was trucked to destination. The residue car will be home shopped for repairs.  NARRI: 2(5±3+0)(2+0)= 32 Cause Code: 551

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DSR CHUCK SMITH UNLOADED A SKID CONTAINING 4 DRUMS FROM TRAILER #315-4903. THE DRUMS WEIGHT HAD BROKEN A BOARD ON THE SKID AND A NAIL PRICKED A PIN HOLE IN THE DRUM. THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM WAS SO THICK AND GLUE LIKE IT ONLY RELEASED ABOUT ONE ONCE AND SEALED ITSELF OFF. DSR CHUCK SMITH PLACED THE DRUM IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND MOVED THE SHIPMENT TO NWN.
column169: CARDBOARD OR PLYWOOD SHOULD HAVE BEEN PLACED UNDER DRUMS BEFORE BEING PLACED ON A SKID.

column168: The package was crushed as well as wet on the bottom when it arrived at Eugene,OR, The unloading driver Benigno Senda notified Service Center Manager George Mikesell upon seeing the wet Carton in Trailer 313-5347 prior to unloading. After unloading George Mikesell opened the wet carton and discovered that there was two cans crushed in the carton, one can was cracked and leaking near the top of the can due to being crushed.
column169: The employees involved need to go over the proper handling of item marked as Hazard Materials to avoid this in the future. At some point during transportation this carton was crushed. It was not posible to determine how this occurred. The cartons were not protected from other freight during transportation from Sacramento, CA. to Eugene, OR.. The loading employee should be trained in the proper use of protective materials we supply to use with hazard materials shipments.

column58: Bolts or Nuts; Manway or Dome Cover
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Human Error; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: At 13:30 hours on Saturday, April 29, 2006, a car inspector during an inbound inspection, heard a hissing sound from SHPX 206752, residue last contained Alcohols, N.O.S., UN 1987. The car inspector reported this to the General Foreman, the PSCC was notified and the HazMat Call Duty Officer was notified. The Selkirk Yard Transportation Emergency Response Plan (TERP) was initiated, and a CSX HazMat Sentinel responded. CSXT Sentinel inspected rail car and found 3 of 6 manway cover bolts were less than tool tight. The bolts were secured and the vapor leak stopped. Chemtrec was notified, report # 04292006026 and NYSDEC was notified, report #0601119. Tank car SHPX 206752 was staged for 6 hours and re-inspected and no vapor leaks were detected. Car was then forwarded for disposition. Cause code= 200  NARRI = 5(4+3+0) X (2+0) = 70

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S., WITH FLASH POINT ABOVE 37.8 C, AT OR ABOVE ITS FLASH POINT
column62: Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: 04/20/06 at 17:00 hrs., CSX Transportation HazMat Manager, S.Michael Austin, was contacted by Jack Bailey of Specialized Professional Services, who was notified by FRA Inspector Matsinger, that UTLX 640774 had what appeared to be slosh leak from the manway. It was determined that six of eight manway bolts were less than tool tight. It was also determined that the manway gasket was also defective. The CSX Transportation Mechanical shop replaced the gasket on the car and all manway bolts were tightened properly and the car was released for transportation.    Cause Code: 200 & 209  NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) =60

column62: Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: CSXT HazMat Manager, S.Michael Austin, received a call from General Car Foreman Carlo, that it appeared a slosh leak was present on UTLX 666911 from the top of the car. Allegany Co. HazMat called to respond to the incident. CSX Transportation dispatched Specialized Professional Services (SPSI) to respond to the incident. Allegany HazMat arrived on site and found that the car was leaking from the 2” ball valve where it screws onto the liquid line. The pressure was relieved on the car and the leak stopped. SPSI arrived on site and determined that no teflon tape/pipe dope was used to lubricate the threads between the ball valve and the liquid line. SPSI used teflon tape and pipe dope to resecure the valve to the liquid line. Ashland Chemical received a FRA movement approval to forward the rail car. On 04/20/06, FRA. Inspector Matsinger, was inspecting this car and discovered the vacuum relief valve was not functioning correctly and advised CSX Transportation that it needed to be fixed prior to the car moving. CSX Transportation notified Ashland Chemical who hired Rescar to replace the valve. Rescar could not do a bubble leak test on the car while it was loaded. Ashland applied for and received an updated movement approval.    Chemtrec Report#041 92006082   Cause Code=283  NARRI: 5(5+ 1 +0)x(2+0)=60

column169: ENSURE COMPLIANCE WITH STANDARD TANK CAR SECUREMENT PROCEDURES PRIOR TO RELEASING CARS FOR TRANSIT.

column168: JACKIE STANDAGE WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING PACKAGE IN THE AURORA CENTER. USING THE PROPER RESPONSE SHEET AND DECISION TREE SHE PROCEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. PACKAGE AND RELATED SPILL WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE DMP CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

PRELOAD FIRST RESPONDER, JHON SINGLETON, WAS CALLED TO THE SOUTH PRIMARY IN THE SORT AISLE AT DOOR 9. HE WORE THE REQUIRED GEAR: BOOTS, APRON, GOGGLES, AND NITRILE GLOVES. HE KNEW IT WAS A HAZARDOUS PACKAGE BECAUSE IT HAD SPECIFIC MARKINGS: I) “FLAMMABLE LIQUID” DIAMOND, 2)SHIPPING PAPERS, 3)ARROWS. JHON USED THE DECISION TREE AND THE PROPER RESPONSE SHEET TO KNOW HOW TO PROCEED WITH THE CLEAN-UP. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE OUTER CONTAINER, THEREFORE, JHON CONTAINERIZE THE WHOLE PACKAGE AND BROUGHT IT BACK TO THE PROCESSING CENTER. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO DISPOSE OF THE WASTE THROUGH THE “WASTE DISPOSAL FOR A FULL DMP FACILITY.” NOTHING WAS ABLE TO BE SENT BACK TO SHIPPER, THEREFORE,NO SALVAGE DRUM WAS NEEDED.

column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Deterioration or Aging
column168: At 12:15 PM on 4-2-06, Frank Lerch, Manager Chemical Transportation Safety was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that tank car AGCX 10076, located at the north end of the Settegast train yard; Houston, TX, was leaking from the manway cover while the car was being moved. The tank car was setout into track 16 for further handling. Upon being notified, Mgr. Lerch advised the RMCC to make shipper notification via Chem-Trec. On arrival and inspection of the car, Mgr. Lerch noted the manway cover gasket to be pinched and cut, resulting in the release of product. Mgr. Lerch removed and replaced the damaged gasket with a temporary Gortex Gasket. Mgr. Lerch then secured and released the car to continue onto destination without further Incident. No product came in contact with the ground as product evaporated upon contacted with the atmosphere. There were no drains, waterways impacted, or reported injuries resulting from this release. At approximately 02:19 PM, Mgr. Lerch spoke with shipper reproeritatie Keith Ford of Methanex Methanol, advising him of the noted problems and corrective actions taken. Original manway seal protecting was Stolihaven #199901; replaced by UPRR CTS 0008798.
column169: Proper post inspection of the car prior to releasing for transportation.    NARR1: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80                                     Code(s): 208, 209N

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Flange; Liquid Line
column168: UPRR Car Department employees reported Tankcar GATX 6651 releasing product from the top of tankcar at Alfalfa yard, El Paso. Mr. John Jackson, Manager Chemical Transportation Safety was notified and responded. Mr. Jackson discovered the tankcar had released product from the liquid line cap due to a defective cap gasket. Mr. Jackson notified the shipper, Western Refinery at El Paso. Western Refinery advised Mr. Jackson they would send a response crew for repairs. Western Refinery personnel responded and replaced defective gasket with like kind. Mr. Jackson notified Viva Environmental to respond, neutralize released product on the car and clean any residue on tank and safety appliances. After Viva completed cleanup, Mr. Jackson inspected the car and released to destination with no other exceptions. Shipper was also notified via Chemtrec.
column169: Shipper notified and discussed loading and unloading procedures at their acid loading ramp.    NARRI: 5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100 Code(s): 249

column168: AT O83OHRS ON 4-5-06, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT TANK CAR GATX 7736 WAS REPORTED LEAKING. CAR WAS ENTRAINED ON TRAIN LHH79-05, LEAD UNIT CEFX 2022 AND WAS STOPPED AT MILEPOST 42.68 ON THE BAYTOWN SUBDIVISION, DAYTON, TX. UPON BEING ADVISED, MGR. LERCH REQUESTED SHIPPER NOTIFICATION BE MADE VIA CHEM-TREC. ON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION  OF CAR, MGR. LERCH NOTED CAR TO BE IN POOR CONDITION. PRODUCT WAS LEAKING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND ONTO THE ROAD BED. WITHIN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING PRODUCT WAS POOLED, AND IT WAS DETERMINED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS DUE TO A FAILED GASKET FROM THE 2 INCH LIQUID LINE FLANGE WHERE IT ATTACHES TO THE FLANGED AND BOLTED MAN WAY COVER PLATE. AFTER DETERMINING THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE, MGP. LERCH VENTED THE CAR, WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE OF ADDITIONAL PRODUCT. AT APPROXIMATELY 213O HRS MGR. LERCH  SPOKE TO BRIAN SOSSAMAN, EMERGENCY RESPONSE MANAGER FOR LYONDELL EQUISTAR ADVISING HIM OF THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE, AND CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN. MR SOSSAMAN INDICATED THAT HE WOULD DISPATCH PERSONNEL TO INSPECT THE CAR, AND BEGIN REMEDIATION EFFORTS. ON ARRIVAL OF EQUISTAR PERSONNEL, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THEY COULD NOT REPAIR THE CAR, AND THAT IT WOULD REQUIRE A MOBIL REPAIR UNIT TO MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS. SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS APPLIED TO THE CAR AND GROUND TO NEUTRALIZE THE AFFECTED AREAS. THE CAR WAS SECURED FROM ANY FURTHER RELEASE AND MOVED TO THE KANAC YARD FOR FURTHER HANDLING THE FOLLOWING MORNING. AT O73OHRS ON 4-6-06, MGR. LERCH REINSPECTED THE CAR NOTING NO FURTHER RELEASE, AND MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE CAR MOVED TO THE DAYTON YARD AND SET-OUT INTO THE G.T. TRACK FOR REPAIRS. MGR. LERCH THEN CONTACTED MR. SOSSAMAN, WH, ADVISED THAT ARRANGEMENTS HAD BEEN MADE TO HAVE RESCAR MOBIL RAILCAR REPAIR RESOND TO MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS. ADDITIONALLY, UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES HAD BEEN DISPATCHED BY MR. SOSSAMAN TO FURTHER REMEDIATE THE AFFECTED AREA. AT 133OHRS RESCAR PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SITE TO INSPECT CAR, AND DETERMINED THAT ADDITIONAL EQUIPMENT AND PARTS WOULD BE NEEDED TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR RESCAR PERSONNEL TO RETURN THE FOLLOWING MORNING AND REPAIR THE CAR. AT O900HRS ON 4-7-06, RESCAR PERSONNEL RETURNED AND REPLACED THE FOUR STAINLESS STEEL STUDS SECURING THE 2 INCH LIQUID BALL VALVE FLANGE AND REPLACED THE FAILED DRIED AND CRACKED FLANGE GASKET. AFTER THE REPAIRS WERE MADE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS AFFECTED OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE. ORIGINAL PROTECTIVE HOUING SEAL# CVO-103195: REPLACED WITH UPRR CTS-0008783.

column168: Richard Jarzombek, Car Foreman, reported a release of product from the top of loaded Tankcar ETCX located in the Sosan Railyard, Yard one, Track 912, San Antonio, TX. Mr. Jarzombek further stated no injuries or exposures occurred and no waterways were affected. Paul Person, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, was notified and responded. All required State notifications were completed. At 07:40 PM, Brian Ramsey, Eastman Chemical Company, requested and received a conference call with Mr. Person concerning the incident. At 07:45 PM, Person advised he stopped the leak and stated the cause was a defective gauging device which resulted in an overfill situation. Mr. Person further advised that released product had evaporated before reaching the ground. The tankcar was being set out on track 111 to be transferred the next day.

UPRR s Response Management Communications Center notified Lane Sekavec, Manager Chemical Transportation Safety, of a tank car reported to be leaking at the One-Spot facility in Kansas City, KS. GATX 18598 was reported to be leaking from the bottom outlet valve. Enroute to the tank car, Mr. Sekavec was advised that shop personnel were able to stop the leak. On arrival, Mr. Sekavec made contact with Rick Gorrell, Car Foreman, who advised one of the carmen stopped the leak by closing the top-operated bottom-outlet valve. He stated the valve was open approximately three-fourths of a turn. Mr. Sekavec checked the car and found the packing gland was loose as well and tightened it. Inspection of the bottom outlet valve nozzle revealed no further release of product. The released product evaporated prior to Mr. Sekavec a arrival and no remediation was possible nor necessary.

column168: The UPRR Car Department Foreman General reported Tankcar TILX 100497 was leaking from top of the car at Alfalfa yard El Paso, TX. John Jackson Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and responded. Mr. Jackson notified Viva Environmental to respond for remediation of contaminated ballast and clean up of the tankcar. Upon arrival at the scene, Mr. Jackson discovered that Western Refinery had been notified and dispatched a response team. Western refinery personnel tightened the liquid education line cap approximately 1 to 1 1/2 turns, stopping the release. Approximately one gallon of product reached the ballast. Viva Environmental neutralized the product on the tankcar and ballast. The tank car and safety appliances were cleaned and rinsed with water. Mr. Jackson removed the liquid education line cap to determine if any gasket material was lodged in the education pipe. After conversation with the shipper, it was determined that no gasket was required on the type of education pipe and cap on this car. Mr. Jackson secured the cap, inspected the tankcar and released it to destination with no other exceptions. Shipper was notified via Chemtrec.
