The Lake Charles, Louisiana terminal was notified by telephone on April 30, 2006, at2:00 a.m. of a discharge by the Louisiana State Police, Trooper Johnny SparkS’ThdIchege Wasominfràrn a trailer T-910 owned by MEMC and being transported by TransWood truck #83154 The discharge occurred in the area of 1-10 West between mile markers 175 and 176. The discharge duration was from 2:00 am. until 4:00p.m. on April 30, 2006.   The tractor/trailer unit was traveling west bound on 1-10 when a police car was chasing a Ford Taurus and passed the tractor trailer at a high rate of speed. When the tractor/trailer approached the top of an overpass, the TransWood driver saw the police car with its emergency lights on and had the Ford Taurus pulled over on the left side of the highway. The TransWood driver had slowed downand was in the right hand lane when the driver of the Ford Taurus puH the highway to the right hand lane in front of the TransWood driver. The TransWood driver moved to the right shoulder to keep from hitting the Ford Taurus and at that point the tractor/trailer hit the grass which caused the driver to loose control of the unit. The tractor/trailer rolled over going down Into the ditch.   One of the tubes on the trailer which was carrying Silicon Tetrafluoride was damaged and started leaking. Product identification: Cas #7738-61-1, DOT #UN 1859. The product loss from the tube was 1600 pounds.   The local fire department sprayed water on the product which is a compressed gas to keep the vapors from discharging into the air. After the tube had completely emptied, the tractor/trailer was up-righted and was towed to Mosaic in Uncle Sam, Louisiana.   The clean up was done by U.S. Environmental Services of Baton Rouge, Louisiana. The clean up crew filled thirteen (13) roll off boxes of soil. brush, and trees. The exact amount in pounds will be determined a disposal time. There was water in the ditch which was tested and the PH levei was six (6) according Raymond Boutte’.   I do not have the name of the driver that was operating the Ford Taurus which caused the accident and subsequent discharge. This information will be available to TransWood when the Louisiana State Police release the accident report. The product was from Mosaic in Uncle Sam, Louisiana, the trailer is owned by MEMC in Pasadena, Texas and the tractor is stationed at TransWood in Lake Charles, Louisiana.   The discharge was non preventable. The vehicle pulled into our lane of traffic and stopped, causing the tractor/trailer to move to the right going into the ditch and rolling over which damaged the trailer tube and caused the discharge   The person doing this report is Richard Thorpe, Held Safety Auditor for TransWood Incorporated. Please contact me shou4d you have any questions or require any further information. Sincerely, Richard Thorpe

column168: 4/28/06. APPROXIMATELY 7:00PM:  WHILE SWITCHING CARS IN THE YARD AT PORT READING, NJ CONDUCTOR-TRAINEE OF CREW PR23 WAS SPRAYED WITH PRODUCT FROM TANK CAR GATX 47185, LOAD, POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLUTION, 8 UN 1814, PG II.  EMPLOYEE REPORTED A "MIST" WHEN CONTACTED ON LOWER FACE, NECK AREA.  EMPLOYEE WASHED AFFECTED AREA WITH WATER FROM HIS WATER BOTTLE, THEN PROCEEDED TO YARD OFFICE AND CONTINUED TO RINSE ALL AFFECTED AREAS FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF HOUR.  EMPLOYEE REFUSED MEDICAL ATTENTION, WENT HOME AND SHOWERED.  NO FURTHER EFFECTS REPORTED.    FURTHER INSPECTION BY CONRAIL'S A. RICHTER, RISK MANAGEMENT, AND CONRAIL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR REACT (REPRESENTED BY R. GOULD) FOUND THE 165 P.S.I. SAFETY VENT FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED AS DESIGNED.  HOWEVER, ALSO NOTED THE CLOSURE/INSPECTION PLUG ON THE SAFETY VENT CLOSURE FLANGE WAS NOT APPLIED.  THIS ACTION APPEARED TO HAVE ALLOWED THE SURGE OF PRODUCT TO SPRAY UP AND OUT OVER THE CAR, PROJECTING THE CAR'S CONTENTS OVER THE TANK CAR, AND FOUR OTHER TANK CARS SURROUNDING IT.  APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD REACHED THE GROUND.  REMAINING PRODUCT ON CARS.  NEW SAFETY VENT FRANGIBLE DISC (COMPATIBLE IN PRESSURE AND MATERIAL) REPLACED, INSPECTION PORT PLUG RESECURED.  EFFECTED CARS MOVED TO #10 RUNNING FOR DECONTAMINATION WITH NEUTRALIZING AGENT THE FOLLOWING DAY.    ON THE FOLLOWING DAY (4/29/06), AFTER CAR HAD BEEN CLEANED/NEUTRALIZED, MANWAY COVER OF UTLX 47185 WAS OPENED TO CHECK OUTAGE OF CONTENTS.  THE CAR'S INTERNAL GAUGE BAR NOTED LIQUID LEVEL AT "5 1/2" (UNSURE IF MASURED IN PERCENTAGE OR INCHES). ALSO, HAND MEASURING FROM THE PRODUCT LEVEL TO THE BOTTOM OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE NOTED TO BE 7".  THIS INFORMATION GIVEN TO SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, FOR THEIR CALCULATION AS TO WHETHER OR NOT THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS ON THE CAR WERE EXAMINED AND NO EXCEPTIONS NOTED.  REMAINING 4 TANK CARS WERE CLEANED/NEUTRALIZED.  CARS OKAYED FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTAION TO ORIGINAL CONSIGNEES.
